{"type": "user", "message": {"role": "user", "content": [{"tool_use_id": "chatcmpl-tool-8f835927c7e5a59d", "type": "tool_result", "content": "1\tarXiv:2607.08526v1 [cs.SD] 9 Jul 2026\n2\t\n3\tA Quantized Native Runtime for On-Device\n4\tSemantic Audio Generation\n5\tMatteo Spanio\n6\t\n7\tAntonio Rodà\n8\t\n9\tCentro di Sonologia Computazionale (CSC)\n10\tDept. of Information Engineering, University of Padova\n11\tPadova, Italy\n12\tspanio@dei.unipd.it\n13\t\n14\tCentro di Sonologia Computazionale (CSC)\n15\tDept. of Information Engineering, University of Padova\n16\tPadova, Italy\n17\troda@dei.unipd.it\n18\t\n19\tAbstract—Semantic audio applications increasingly require\n20\tcontrollable generation on commodity and embedded hardware\n21\trather than through framework-heavy datacenter stacks. We\n22\tpresent aria, a dependency-free native runtime that runs the\n23\tcomplete text-to-music pipeline of Stable Audio 3 (SA3) on\n24\tordinary GPUs, CPU-only machines, and a Raspberry Pi 5, with\n25\tno Python or deep-learning framework underneath. Our main\n26\tcontribution is a study of quantization: running the model at\n27\tlower numerical precision to fit tight memory budgets, saving\n28\tmemory in place rather than adding to it. Because the runtime\n29\towns every internal tensor, it also exposes activation steering,\n30\ta low-cost way to steer what the model generates. We judge\n31\tthe quality cost with three independent measures of the output\n32\t(prompt adherence, overall audio quality, taste preservation),\n33\teach compared against the ordinary variation between random\n34\tseeds. Eight-bit precision shows no measurable quality loss on\n35\tany measure while sharply cutting memory, and it is the fastest\n36\tmode on the GPU; four-bit adds a small, bounded cost but shrinks\n37\tthe footprint enough to run the 1.2-billion-parameter model on\n38\tan 8 GB Pi. Against the official implementation, aria matches\n39\tor exceeds generation speed and starts about seven times faster.\n40\tA case study of the steering interface generates music carrying\n41\ttaste associations (sonic seasoning), with genuine but bounded\n42\tcontrol for a subset of attributes. These results make a compact,\n43\tquantized runtime with built-in control a practical basis for ondevice semantic audio in Internet-of-Sounds settings. The aria\n44\truntime is released at https://github.com/matteospanio/aria.\n45\tIndex Terms—efficient inference, model quantization, edge\n46\tcomputing, audio diffusion, music generation, activation steering\n47\t\n48\tI. I NTRODUCTION\n49\tSemantic audio generation is moving from cloud demos\n50\ttoward interactive tools, local creative services, and embedded\n51\taudio devices [1]. These settings care not only about generation quality but also about deployment properties: cold-start\n52\tlatency, predictable memory use, portability across commodity\n53\tCPUs and GPUs, and the ability to keep a model resident\n54\tnear the user. Open-weight music models are now strong\n55\tenough to be useful in such systems, yet their reference\n56\timplementations still assume a Python/PyTorch serving stack\n57\tand a discrete GPU. That mismatch matters for Internet-ofSounds applications, where semantic audio often needs to\n58\trun as a local or edge service rather than as a heavyweight\n59\tdatacenter job.\n60\tLocal-inference work suggests a way forward, from the\n61\tdependency-free llama.cpp family [2] to portable engines such\n62\t\n63\trented / framework-bound\n64\t\n65\t11.6–22.2 s cold start\n66\tStable Audio 3\n67\tofficial PyTorch stack\n68\tOOM at load on 8 GB\n69\t\n70\t15–48 s compile / length\n71\t\n72\taria\n73\tC/CUDA, zero deps\n74\t\n75\tCUDA graph + NEON\n76\t\n77\twindowed decode\n78\t\n79\t1\n80\t\n81\towned / one binary\n82\t\n83\tprompt\n84\t\n85\tsame checkpoints\n86\t\n87\tT5\n88\t\n89\tdecoder\n90\t3\n91\t\n92\t1.6–2.9 s cold, 7×\n93\t\n94\tDiT blocks\n95\t\n96\t0.13 s warm, ≤ SAT\n97\t\n98\taudio\n99\t\n100\t2\n101\t\n102\tPi 5: both models\n103\t\n104\tFig. 1. With aria, the same Stable Audio 3 checkpoints move from a\n105\tframework-bound serving stack (top) to a single dependency-free binary on\n106\thardware people own (bottom): 7× faster cold start, warm parity, and both\n107\tmodel variants on a Raspberry Pi 5. Owning the pipeline also makes activation\n108\tsteering a runtime feature, injected at 1 the DiT residual stream, 2 the latent,\n109\tor 3 the text conditioning.\n110\t\n111\tas ONNX Runtime [3] and DwarfStar’s port of datacenterscale language models to user hardware [4]. The engineering\n112\tlesson is general: once the serving stack is removed, model\n113\tclasses once treated as cloud-only can become practical on\n114\towned hardware.\n115\tAudio generation is a particularly strong candidate for this\n116\tshift. Open music models are much smaller than frontier\n117\tlanguage models, roughly 1–10 B parameters, and diffusion\n118\tinference scales with denoising steps rather than the far longer\n119\tacoustic token sequences of autoregressive systems. The two\n120\tleading open-source music generators, ACE-Step 1.5 [5] and\n121\tStable Audio [6], are both built on diffusion transformers\n122\t(DiTs). We take Stable Audio 3 (SA3) as the reference target\n123\tand ask a systems question: how much of its deployment cost\n124\tbelongs to the model itself, and how much belongs to the\n125\tsurrounding framework?\n126\tWe answer that question with aria, a dependency-free\n127\tC/CUDA runtime for SA3 that runs the full text-to-music\n128\tpipeline, both model variants, on commodity GPUs and CPU-\n129\t\n130\t\fonly hardware (Figure 1). The runtime executes the tokenizer,\n131\ttext encoder, transformer denoiser, and autoencoder in a single\n132\tnative stack, stores weights from half precision down to 8- or\n133\t4-bit integers, runs the arithmetic in 8-bit where it pays off,\n134\tand holds long-form generation within bounded memory. On a\n135\tRaspberry Pi 5 (8 GB), the small model generates a 10 s stereo\n136\tclip at a 1.9 GB full-precision peak, which quantization cuts\n137\tto 0.84 GB at 8-bit. The 1.2 B-parameter medium model runs\n138\tCPU-only at 4-bit (∼200 s; 0.9 GB resident, 3.6 GB peak).\n139\tA native runtime also owns every intermediate tensor, which\n140\tmakes activation steering a runtime primitive rather than a\n141\tPython-side patch or a retrained adapter: directions can be\n142\tinjected into the generation graph at negligible cost, giving\n143\tsemantic control while preserving the runtime’s deployment\n144\tadvantages.\n145\tWe use sonic seasoning, taste-conditioned music generation,\n146\tas a case study for this capability [7], [8]. Taste is a useful\n147\tstress test because it is difficult to specify lexically, grounded\n148\tin an external crossmodal literature, and therefore informative\n149\tabout whether a learned steering target captures genuine\n150\tsemantic change or merely responds to degradation.\n151\tWe make four contributions. (i) The aria runtime: a\n152\tdependency-free C/CUDA engine that runs SA3’s full pipeline\n153\t(text encoder, transformer denoiser, autoencoder) on GPUs,\n154\tCPU-only systems, and embedded-class hardware, with a\n155\tcalibrated efficiency study against the official implementation\n156\tacross warm latency, cold start, peak memory, and CPUonly generation. (ii) A deployment quantization study:\n157\tweight storage from half precision down to 4-bit and an 8bit-arithmetic mode on GPU tensor cores and ARM, made\n158\tmemory-frugal by releasing the full-precision weights once\n159\tcompressed. Rather than assume a fidelity budget, we measure the quality cost with three independent checks (prompt\n160\tadherence, distributional quality, and taste preservation). On all\n161\tthree, 8-bit stays within re-seed noise, and 4-bit is sufficient,\n162\tat a measurable but bounded cost, to put a 1.2 B model on\n163\tan 8 GB Pi. (iii) An in-graph activation-steering interface\n164\twith zero measurable overhead, bit-exact disable behaviour,\n165\tand dose-response parity with the reference. (iv) A bounded\n166\tsemantic-control case study that uses sonic seasoning to test\n167\ta hard-to-lexicalize attribute under a multi-oracle protocol. The\n168\tresult is a quantized native runtime with in-graph control, a\n169\tpractical basis for on-device semantic audio generation.\n170\tII. R ELATED W ORK\n171\t\n172\tcross-attention and trained with flow matching [12]. We study\n173\tits small-music (20 DiT blocks, dmodel =1024) and medium\n174\t(24 blocks, dmodel =1536) configurations. The DiT residual\n175\tstream of per-block hidden states is the substrate that activation\n176\tsteering reads and writes. The broader shift toward live generation, exemplified by Magenta / Lyria RealTime [13], makes\n177\twarm, resident runtimes more attractive than cold per-request\n178\tprocesses.\n179\tB. Generative models on edge devices\n180\tState-of-the-art generative audio increasingly runs behind\n181\tclosed APIs such as Suno1 and Udio2 . Open-weight reference stacks, by contrast, are typically heavyweight Python\n182\tpipelines that assume a discrete GPU, and community CPU\n183\tports of SA3 remain tied to PyTorch [14]. The ggml lineage (llama.cpp [2], whisper.cpp [15], DwarfStar [4], stablediffusion.cpp [16]) shows that a single, self-contained C/C++\n184\tprogram with memory-mapped weights, low-bit quantization,\n185\tand hand-written vector and GPU kernels can deliver interactive inference on consumer hardware with near-zero cold start.\n186\tPortability-first engines such as ONNX Runtime [3], ExecuTorch [17], Apple MLX [18], and NVIDIA TensorRT [19]\n187\ttrade model-specific kernels for generic graph execution. Neither approach has yet reached latent-diffusion music: to our\n188\tknowledge, no dependency-free C runtime exists for a stateof-the-art music model, a gap that aria fills.\n189\tC. Quantization for on-device diffusion\n190\tLow-bit inference is the lever that makes these runtimes\n191\tfit budget hardware. Post-training quantization (PTQ) compresses LLMs to 8-bit weights and activations without retraining [20], diffusion-specific PTQ pushes image models to 4-bit\n192\tweights [21], and PTQ has recently been extended to audio\n193\tdiffusion transformers [22]. These works tune the quantizer\n194\tfor a fixed fidelity target. We instead address deployment. Our\n195\tnative runtime treats precision as a first-class axis, spanning\n196\thalf-precision, 8-bit, and 4-bit storage plus 8-bit arithmetic.\n197\tBy releasing the full-precision weights once compressed, it\n198\tmakes lower precision a memory replacement rather than\n199\tan addition. It ships hardware-specific 8-bit kernels (integer\n200\ttensor cores on the GPU, the matching instruction on ARM),\n201\tand gates each precision against fp16 on independent objective\n202\tchecks of prompt adherence, distributional quality, and taste\n203\tpreservation.\n204\t\n205\tA. Generative audio models\n206\t\n207\tD. Steering techniques\n208\t\n209\tText-to-music systems fall into two broad families: autoregressive transformers over discrete acoustic tokens, and\n210\tlatent-diffusion models that denoise in the latent space of a\n211\tneural audio autoencoder. Diffusion cost scales with denoising\n212\tsteps rather than sequence length, and the leading openweight systems, ACE-Step [5] and the Stable Audio family,\n213\tare DiT-based. Our reference is Stable Audio 3 (SA3) [6].\n214\tIt couples a SAME semantic-acoustic autoencoder [9], a\n215\t256-dimensional continuous latent, to a diffusion-transformer\n216\t(DiT) denoiser [10] conditioned on text via T5Gemma [11]\n217\t\n218\tA frozen generative model can be controlled either by\n219\tediting its weights or by intervening on its activations at\n220\tinference time. The activation-based route rests on the linear\n221\trepresentation hypothesis, according to which interpretable\n222\tattributes are encoded approximately as linear directions in\n223\thidden space. Adding one vector to the residual stream can\n224\ttherefore shift an attribute while leaving the rest of the\n225\t1 https://suno.com, accessed 2026-07-04.\n226\t2 https://www.udio.com, accessed 2026-07-04.\n227\t\n228\t\fcomputation intact. Activation addition [23] and representation engineering [24] extract such directions from contrastive\n229\texamples and inject them at generation time. Tan et al. [25]\n230\tcharacterize when these vectors generalize. This paradigm\n231\tis now well represented in audio and music [26]–[31]. We\n232\ttake our injection design from Camporese et al. [26]. The\n233\tweight-based family (LoRA [32], ControlNet [33], concept\n234\tsliders [34]) can provide strong control, but it requires training,\n235\tper-attribute data, and a growing parameter footprint. LoRA,\n236\tthe de-facto parameter-efficient standard, is our training-based\n237\tcomparator. Our case study targets a gustatory attribute, the\n238\tfive basic tastes: “sonic seasoning” reports reliable crossmodal\n239\tassociations between tastes and acoustic parameters [35],\n240\t[36]. They are stable enough to shift the perceived taste of\n241\tfood [37], [38], and Spence later synthesized them under the\n242\tlabel of gastrophysics [39]. These correspondences ground the\n243\treference used to assess steered generation; Section III gives\n244\tthe mapping.\n245\tIII. M ETHODOLOGY\n246\tA. The aria runtime\n247\taria carries the dependency-free native-runtime discipline\n248\tof Section II over to audio latent diffusion. It targets the\n249\ttwo settings in which the official Stable Audio 3 PyTorch\n250\tstack is least practical: interactive or live generation from\n251\ta resident service [13], and budget or CPU-only inference,\n252\twhere framework startup, GPU-context setup, and a multisecond cold start dominate short generations. aria is a singlepurpose engine for SA3 in about 7.7k lines of C and CUDA,\n253\twith no linear-algebra library, deep-learning framework, or\n254\tother third-party dependency beyond the C math library and\n255\ta threading runtime. It implements the whole pipeline behind\n256\ta small dispatch layer: a text tokenizer, the T5Gemma text\n257\tencoder [11], the diffusion transformer (DiT) that denoises the\n258\taudio latent over eight sampling steps, and the audio autoencoder [9] (a 256-dimensional latent at ∼10.7 Hz). Supporting\n259\ta new architecture adds one file and a registry entry, not a\n260\tkernel rewrite. Weights are mapped directly from disk in half\n261\tprecision (fp16), with full precision (fp32) kept only where\n262\tfidelity is sensitive. Optional lower-precision storage, down\n263\tto 8- or 4-bit integers, keeps the medium model and smallmemory GPUs within budget; once the compressed copy exists\n264\tthe runtime releases the original, so a lower precision replaces\n265\trather than adds to the footprint, cutting the Pi’s peak memory\n266\tfrom 1.9 to 0.84 GB at 8-bit.\n267\tOne set of operations runs behind two backends. The\n268\tCPU path is vectorized and multi-threaded, carries an 8-bitinteger matrix-multiply variant, and doubles as the correctness\n269\treference and the CPU-only production target. The GPU path\n270\tuses half-precision tensor-core matrix multiplies and attention,\n271\tincluding a banded decoder kernel; its per-step denoising\n272\tloop is captured once and replayed as a single GPU graph.\n273\tA windowed decoder caps memory at byte-identical output,\n274\tand a streaming variant decodes only the frames it emits\n275\t(3.1× faster per chunk on the Pi, still byte-identical); together\n276\tthey let the runtime generate and stream long-form audio\n277\t\n278\ton a Raspberry Pi 5. A resident batch mode and an HTTP\n279\tserver keep the model loaded across jobs for multi-client\n280\tserving, roughly doubling throughput (0.60 vs. 1.23 s per job)\n281\tat identical output.\n282\ta) Steering interface.: Because the runtime owns every\n283\tintermediate tensor, activation steering becomes a built-in\n284\tfeature rather than a Python-side patch. aria loads precomputed direction vectors and applies them at three points in\n285\tthe pipeline, either adding the direction or projecting onto\n286\tit and optionally only during a chosen span of sampling\n287\tsteps: the transformer’s residual stream, the compact audio\n288\tlatent, and the text conditioning. This reproduces the reference\n289\tˆ Section III). On the GPU\n290\tintervention exactly (δ = α∥h∥ d;\n291\tthe steering step lives inside the captured graph and reads a\n292\tstrength value refreshed each step (zero outside the chosen\n293\tspan), so enabling it triggers no re-capture and adds no\n294\tmeasurable overhead; at strength 0 the output is bit-identical\n295\tto the base model. The taste case study of Section III is thus\n296\ta property of the runtime, not a fork of it.\n297\tb) Quantization and its evaluation.: The transformer’s\n298\tweights can be stored in half precision, or compressed to 8-bit\n299\tor 4-bit integers (labelled q8 and q4). An optional mode also\n300\truns the arithmetic in 8-bit, quantizing activations alongside\n301\tweights (W8A8), on the GPU’s integer tensor cores or the\n302\tequivalent ARM instruction. Because the compressed copy\n303\towns its memory, the runtime frees the full-precision source\n304\tonce packed, so a lower precision reduces resident memory\n305\trather than adding to it. We gate each precision empirically\n306\tagainst the fp16 output on three independent objective checks\n307\t(Section IV-B0a, Table II) rather than assuming a fidelity\n308\tbudget.\n309\tc) Efficiency protocol.: To compare deployments fairly,\n310\twe separate three regimes. Warm generation, with the model\n311\talready resident in-process on both sides, is the cost a live\n312\tor batched service pays per request. Invocation is a one-shot\n313\tcommand-line call that additionally re-pays per-process setup\n314\t(text encoding and moving weights to the GPU). Cold start is\n315\tprocess launch plus weight load plus one generation, the cost\n316\tan edge endpoint pays on first use. We report all three on an\n317\tRTX 3070 GPU and a CPU-only tier (Table I), analyzed in\n318\tSection IV-B.\n319\tB. Taste steering and sonic seasoning\n320\tSonic seasoning is the crossmodal finding that\n321\tmusic systematically shifts perceived taste (consonant\n322\thigh-pitched legato reads as sweet, dissonant low\n323\tmusic as bitter) across the five basic-taste axes\n324\t{sweet, sour, bitter, salty, spicy} [35]–[38]. We ask whether\n325\ta frozen music generator can be steered to produce audio\n326\tcarrying these associations. The machinery steers any\n327\tdifference-in-means direction. We choose taste as a difficult\n328\tattribute that remains externally measurable: continuous,\n329\tweakly lexicalized, and grounded in an independent\n330\tpsychophysics literature. We treat SA3 (Section III-A) as a\n331\tblack box and intervene on its activations. The taste oracle\n332\twe optimize is susceptible to metric gaming, so a multi-oracle\n333\t\n334\t\fh̄±\n335\ti,ℓ =\n336\t\n337\t1 X 1\n338\thℓ (x)t .\n339\tT t=1\n340\t|Si± |\n341\t±\n342\tx∈Si\n343\t\n344\t(1)\n345\tThe contrast comes from two sources. Prompt-side sets are\n346\tcaption pairs differing only in a taste descriptor, self-contained\n347\tbut encoding only what the text encoder associates with that\n348\tword. Audio-side sets ground the contrast in the reference\n349\tdataset [40], 377 music clips with per-clip basic-taste ratings.\n350\tWe rank these by rating on i and feed the top-/bottom-k clips\n351\tto SA3 as an initial audio input, capturing the residuals it\n352\tproduces on audio humans actually heard as sweet or sour.\n353\tAudio-side directions are more monotonic and more robust\n354\tto over-steering, so we use them by default while retaining\n355\tprompt-side directions as a controlled comparison.\n356\t2) Additive injection: At inference we add a scaled copy of\n357\tthe direction to the chosen block’s output, for a single strength\n358\tα ≥ 0,\n359\t(ℓ)\n360\th ← h + α ∥h̄∥ di ,\n361\t(2)\n362\twhere ∥h̄∥ is the mean baseline residual norm at ℓ, so α is\n363\tin units of the typical residual magnitude, comparable across\n364\tblocks and both model sizes. The intervention touches one\n365\tblock, adds one rank-one term, and has one hyperparameter.\n366\tSetting α = 0 leaves the pass unchanged and gives the\n367\tmatched, seed-identical baseline. We sweep α up to 1.0\n368\tbecause the response is non-monotonic: a useful regime exists\n369\tonly at low strength, while larger α severely degrades the\n370\taudio.\n371\t3) Training-based baseline: per-axis LoRA: To quantify\n372\twhat training-free steering sacrifices, we train a per-axis\n373\tLoRA [32] (r = 8) on the same contrasts with the backbone\n374\tfrozen, using a trigger-token objective (high-i clips captioned\n375\t“i taste” vs. a neutral “music”). Unlike steering, it needs a\n376\tper-axis optimization run, adds served parameters, and cannot\n377\tbe removed by zeroing a scalar. Both arms share the extraction\n378\tdata, pipeline, and evaluation, and each method’s cost is\n379\tlogged (Section IV-C0g).\n380\t4) Multi-oracle evaluation: The central risk is circularity:\n381\tthe quantity we optimize is also the quantity one might\n382\tbe tempted to report as evidence of success. Our target is\n383\twav2taste [41], a learned audio-to-taste regressor. The effect\n384\ton axis i is ∆i (α) = τbi (xα ) − τbi (x0 ) against the matched\n385\tα = 0 baseline. But wav2taste is imperfect (held-out macro\n386\tPearson r ≈ 0.67; best sweet 0.82, worst sour 0.59) and\n387\tcan over-score out-of-distribution audio. We therefore guard\n388\tit with three independent oracles: CLAP [42], [43] text–\n389\taudio similarity to “X-tasting music” anchors, which shares\n390\t\n391\tCLAP\n392\t\n393\t=\n394\t\n395\tT\n396\tX\n397\t\n398\tFAD\n399\t\n400\t(ℓ)\n401\t\n402\tdi\n403\t\n404\t−\n405\th̄+\n406\ti,ℓ − h̄i,ℓ\n407\t,\n408\t−\n409\th̄+\n410\ti,ℓ − h̄i,ℓ 2\n411\t\n412\tsour (L19): oracles agree only at low\n413\twav2taste\n414\t\n415\tprotocol distinguishes genuine control from degradation that\n416\tartificially raises the target.\n417\t1) Direction and injection site: Each DiT block writes its\n418\tupdate additively, so its output lies in the same dmodel space as\n419\tits input. For axis i and block ℓ we estimate a unit direction\n420\t(ℓ)\n421\tdi pointing from “low-i” to “high-i” by difference-in-means,\n422\tthe simplest estimator known to transfer [23]–[26], over each\n423\tcontrastive set Si± :\n424\t\n425\ttarget (steered metric)\n426\t\n427\t0.4\n428\t0.2\n429\t\n430\tgenuine\n431\twindow\n432\t\n433\t0.0\n434\t2\n435\t0\n436\t2\n437\t4\n438\t\n439\tindependent semantic check\n440\t\n441\t1000\n442\tdegradation\n443\t\n444\t0\n445\t\n446\t0.2\n447\t\n448\t0.4\n449\t\n450\t0.6\n451\t\n452\tsteering strength\n453\t\n454\t0.8\n455\t\n456\t1.0\n457\t\n458\tFig. 2. The degradation demonstration (SOUR, small-music, its best layer\n459\tL19), as two stacked panels sharing α (no dual axis). Top: the steering\n460\ttarget (wav2taste ∆, with a 95% bootstrap CI band over the paired per-clip\n461\tdeltas) and the independent CLAP ∆ on one axis; both rise inside the shaded\n462\tlow-α genuine window, then diverge as wav2taste stays high while CLAP\n463\tcollapses. Bottom: FAD explodes past the window. The high-α wav2taste\n464\tgain is degradation that games the oracle. Colours are the fixed colourblindsafe taste palette (CLAP/FAD are shown neutral, being independent checks\n465\trather than tastes).\n466\t\n467\tno training signal, as a semantic cross-check; Fréchet Audio\n468\tDistance (FAD) [44] over CLAP embeddings as a degradation detector; and audio drift, 1 − cos(ϕ(xα ), ϕ(x0 )) on\n469\tCLAP embeddings, as perturbation magnitude. All clips are\n470\tloudness-normalized to −14 LUFS first, so no metric moves\n471\tby loudness. We treat a setting as genuine only when ∆i and\n472\tCLAP rise together at low drift and bounded FAD. When ∆i\n473\trises while CLAP falls and FAD or drift increase, we report\n474\tdegradation instead. A two-stage funnel locates this regime:\n475\ta target-only per-layer scan nominates a candidate block per\n476\taxis, then a dense α-window at that block is selected by all\n477\tfour oracles. The nomination is target-only by design. It is a\n478\tcheap localizer, while the multi-oracle window is the actual\n479\tgate, so the reported operating point is never chosen by the\n480\ttarget alone. That ordering also exposes the failure mode. The\n481\tscan ranks the final block first for the intense tastes, but the\n482\toracle panel then overturns that block as degradation (Section\n483\tIV-C0b). A multi-oracle nomination would have hidden this\n484\trather than surfaced it. The candidate block is retained only if\n485\tit survives the panel. Otherwise its clean operating point, or\n486\tthe axis, is rejected.\n487\t\n488\t\fTABLE I\n489\tRUNTIME EFFICIENCY OF aria VERSUS THE OFFICIAL S TABLE AUDIO 3 P Y T ORCH IMPLEMENTATION : 10 S CLIP, 8 SAMPLING STEPS , STEERING ACTIVE ,\n490\tON AN RTX 3070 (8 GB) WITH AN I 9-10900KF (CPU- ONLY ROWS USE 20 THREADS ). Warm = GENERATION WITH THE MODEL ALREADY RESIDENT\n491\tIN - PROCESS ( BOTH SIDES ); invocation = A ONE - SHOT COMMAND - LINE CALL THAT RE - PAYS PER - PROCESS SETUP ; cold = PROCESS SPAWN + WEIGHT\n492\tLOAD + ONE GENERATION . VRAM IS THE PEAK GPU PROCESS FOOTPRINT; “–” WHERE NOT APPLICABLE .\n493\t\n494\tsmall-music\n495\tConfiguration\n496\t\n497\tmedium\n498\t\n499\tTime (s)\n500\t\n501\tVRAM (MB)\n502\t\n503\tTime (s)\n504\t\n505\tVRAM (MB)\n506\t\n507\taria GPU (warm)\n508\taria GPU (invocation)\n509\taria (cold start)\n510\taria CPU-only\n511\t\n512\t0.13\n513\t1.23\n514\t1.6\n515\t2.5\n516\t\n517\t1395\n518\t–\n519\t–\n520\t–\n521\t\n522\t0.37\n523\t2.55\n524\t2.9\