ked by the target metric\n927\talone. One candidate block per axis is then submitted to the\n928\toracle panel for confirmation or rejection.\n929\tb) Dense\n930\twindow\n931\tand\n932\toracle\n933\tpanel:\n934\tAt\n935\teach axis’s best layer on small-music we sweep\n936\tα ∈ {0.1, 0.15, 0.2, 0.3, 0.5, 0.7, 1.0} over 12 prompts\n937\t× 3 seeds, scoring every clip with the four-oracle panel of\n938\tSection III (wav2taste target, CLAP cross-check, FAD, drift).\n939\tA model-size study repeats the sweet sweep on medium,\n940\twith each model evaluated at its own re-scanned best layer.\n941\tc) Ablation designs: Three ablation families reuse the\n942\tdense-window panel on small-music. Injection op: besides\n943\tadditive steering we test projection, amplifying (β>0) or\n944\tremoving (β<0) the direction component already present per\n945\ttoken, swept both ways. Step window: injection confined to the\n946\tearly (0–3) vs. late (4–7) denoise steps at matched strength.\n947\tSteering site: the same difference-in-means recipe applied to\n948\tthe compact audio latent and the pooled text embedding,\n949\tcomparing residual, latent, and text injection. The training\n950\tcomparator is the per-axis rank-8 LoRA of Section III (800\n951\tsteps), dose-swept and scored with the same panel.\n952\td) aria reproduction and efficiency: To confirm the runtime preserves steering behaviour, we re-run the dense window\n953\tthrough aria with the identical exported direction vectors and\n954\tα grid, and report per-axis Pearson r and MAE against the\n955\tSA3/PyTorch reference on the wav2taste and CLAP doseresponses. Efficiency is measured on the RTX 3070 and a\n956\tCPU-only x86 tier under the warm / invocation / cold protocol\n957\tof Section III-A (Table I). The baseline is the official Stable\n958\tAudio 3 implementation (commit dedace19, 2026-07-01;\n959\ttorch 2.7.1, CUDA 12.6), run in half precision with its native\n960\t8-step sampler and no classifier-free guidance. With the faster\n961\tattention kernel unavailable, the repository’s fallback attention\n962\tpath is active, and reported memory is the process’s GPU\n963\tfootprint. The repository disables several standard performance\n964\toptions by default; we measured both that default and a\n965\ttuned configuration (those options enabled, plus compiling the\n966\ttransformer) and cite the faster one throughout.\n967\te) Quantization fidelity: We characterize each precision\n968\tagainst fp16 rather than fixing a fidelity budget. Every clip is\n969\tgenerated on the GPU with the decoder held at half precision,\n970\tso a comparison isolates the transformer’s weight (q8, q4) or\n971\tweight-plus-activation (W8A8) quantization from any device\n972\teffect. We use 24 genre-diverse music prompts × 3 seeds\n973\t(72 clips per precision, 10 s, loudness-normalized). We score\n974\tthree metrics drawn from two independent audio models.\n975\tTwo come from CLAP [43], a text–audio embedding model:\n976\tprompt adherence (how closely each clip matches its own text\n977\tprompt) and distributional quality (Fréchet Audio Distance,\n978\tFAD [44], between the precision’s clips and the fp16 set in\n979\t\n980\t\fTABLE V\n981\tC ONSOLIDATED OPERATING POINTS FOR THE INJECTION - OP, STEP - WINDOW, STEERING - SITE , AND METHOD ABLATIONS ( SMALL - MUSIC , FP 32; n=36\n982\tCLIPS PER POINT, 12 PROMPTS × 3 SEEDS ). ∆ W 2 T IS THE WAV 2 TASTE TARGET SHIFT VS . THE MATCHED α=0 BASELINE ; ∆CLAP IS THE INDEPENDENT\n983\tSEMANTIC CHECK ( BOLD ONCE IT HAS FLIPPED NEGATIVE , I . E . OFF THE GENUINE WINDOW ); FAD IS DEGRADATION VS . BASELINE . T HE FOUR GROUPS\n984\tARE READ IN THE STEERING RESULTS (S ECTION IV-C).\n985\tOp-point\n986\t\n987\t∆w2t\n988\t\n989\t∆CLAP\n990\t\n991\tFAD\n992\t\n993\tα=0.1\n994\tα=0.15\n995\tβ=1\n996\tα=0.3\n997\t\n998\t+0.419\n999\t+0.522\n1000\t+0.492\n1001\t+0.119\n1002\t\n1003\t+1.77\n1004\t−0.63\n1005\t+0.60\n1006\t+2.11\n1007\t\n1008\t561\n1009\t985\n1010\t544\n1011\t515\n1012\t\n1013\tDenoise-step window (DiT residual, sour)\n1014\tsour\n1015\tearly (steps 0–3)\n1016\tα=0.2\n1017\tlate (steps 4–7)\n1018\tα=0.2\n1019\t\n1020\t+0.530\n1021\t+0.515\n1022\t\n1023\t−4.26\n1024\t+0.80\n1025\t\n1026\t1294\n1027\t565\n1028\t\n1029\tSteering site\n1030\tsour\n1031\tlatent (256-D)\n1032\tsweet\n1033\tlatent (256-D)\n1034\tsour\n1035\ttext (768-D)\n1036\t\n1037\tscale 1\n1038\tscale 0.5\n1039\tscale 0.5\n1040\t\n1041\t+0.385\n1042\t+0.050\n1043\t+0.299\n1044\t\n1045\t+1.34\n1046\t+0.69\n1047\t−3.04\n1048\t\n1049\t365\n1050\t197\n1051\t935\n1052\t\n1053\tMethod: LoRA vs. best steering\n1054\tsour\n1055\tLoRA\n1056\tα=1.0\n1057\tsweet\n1058\tLoRA\n1059\tα=0.5\n1060\tsour\n1061\tsteering\n1062\tproj. β=1\n1063\tsweet\n1064\tsteering\n1065\tadd. α=0.3\n1066\t\n1067\t+0.341\n1068\t+0.032\n1069\t+0.492\n1070\t+0.119\n1071\t\n1072\t−0.92\n1073\t−0.10\n1074\t+0.60\n1075\t+2.11\n1076\t\n1077\t767\n1078\t171\n1079\t544\n1080\t515\n1081\t\n1082\tAxis\n1083\t\n1084\tMethod / site\n1085\t\n1086\tInjection op (DiT residual)\n1087\tsour\n1088\tadditive\n1089\tadditive\n1090\tprojection\n1091\tsweet\n1092\tadditive\n1093\t\n1094\ta 32-dimensional embedding space, reduced for stability at\n1095\tthis sample size). The third, from the separate wav2taste [41]\n1096\tmodel, is taste preservation (the distance between the 5-D\n1097\ttaste vectors of each clip and its fp16 counterpart). Re-seeding\n1098\tfp16 (seeds 3–5) gives each metric a reference-noise floor, the\n1099\tchange a re-seed alone induces; a precision is within noise\n1100\tbelow it.\n1101\t\n1102\t1.68× faster (48.0 vs. 80.65 s), and the small-tier CPU gap to\n1103\tthe PyTorch baseline essentially closes (1.09×). The official\n1104\twarm figure relies on the reference’s kernel compiler, which\n1105\trecompiles for each new clip length (a 14.5–48.1 s penalty,\n1106\tpoorly suited to varying lengths); its medium loader also\n1107\tbriefly needs ∼7.1 GB, overflowing an 8 GB card, so the\n1108\tbenchmark used a low-memory load path.\n1109\t\n1110\tB. Runtime benchmarks\n1111\t\n1112\ta) Quantization is close to free at 8-bit, and enables\n1113\tthe edge: Precision is a deployment axis, so we characterize\n1114\trather than fix it (Table II, Figure 4) with the three checks\n1115\tof Section IV-A0e. To avoid validating quantization with the\n1116\tsame oracle the steering study optimizes, we lead with the\n1117\ttwo msclap-based metrics that share no training path with the\n1118\ttaste oracle: prompt adherence and FAD. We keep the networkindependent wav2taste L2 as a narrow corroborator, and scale\n1119\teach metric by the change a fp16 re-seed induces. Eight-bit\n1120\tshows no measurable degradation on any of the three. Both q8\n1121\tand W8A8 stay inside every re-seed floor while cutting GPU\n1122\tmemory ∼21% and Pi resident memory 2.3×, and W8A8 is\n1123\tthe fastest GPU mode (0.10 s warm, on the GPU’s integer\n1124\ttensor cores). Four-bit measurably crosses every floor, most\n1125\ton prompt adherence (5× its floor). It nonetheless lets the\n1126\t1.2 B medium model run on the 8 GB Pi (∼200 s); fidelity\n1127\there is small-music, and the medium case is a memory-fit\n1128\tresult. fp16 reproduces the fp32 dose–response (r=1.00, MAE\n1129\t0.003; steering sweep), so precision is not confounded with\n1130\tthe model-scale results below.\n1131\t\n1132\tTable I reports the three deployment regimes across both\n1133\ttiers. In the warm setting, with the model resident on both\n1134\tsides, aria slightly edges the official implementation after a\n1135\tround of kernel tuning and request reuse. A steered 10 s clip\n1136\truns in 0.13 vs. 0.146 s (small-music) and 0.37 vs. 0.443 s\n1137\t(medium). It cold-starts 7.2–7.7× faster and holds a 1.4–\n1138\t1.7× smaller peak GPU-memory footprint (Table I), and its\n1139\tresident batch mode amortizes per-process setup to 0.60 s per\n1140\tjob. The runtime also operates without a GPU. After a pass that\n1141\tparallelizes and vectorizes the elementwise work between the\n1142\tmatrix multiplies, a 10 s clip decodes in 2.5 s on small-music\n1143\t(∼4× real time) and 9.8 s on medium on a 20-thread CPU,\n1144\tand chunked sliding-window generation streams at a real-time\n1145\tfactor of 0.6–4× on the RTX 3070. A calibrated fast preset\n1146\t(six denoising steps instead of eight) trims a further ∼25%\n1147\toff every transformer-bound path, with a taste-shift below the\n1148\tseed-to-seed noise floor on both tiers.\n1149\tAt 60 s on GPU the picture inverts on the medium tier. A\n1150\thalf-precision attention output stage and running the mapping\n1151\tconvolution as a matrix multiply put aria at 1.28 s against\n1152\tthe reference’s fused-attention path at 1.38 s, faster at equal\n1153\tprecision. An opt-in 8-bit-arithmetic mode (W8A8, of 4-bitclass fidelity) extends the lead to 1.12 s. Only on small-music,\n1154\twhere self-attention dominates the smaller autoencoder, does\n1155\tthe official path stay ahead (0.52 vs. 0.38 s, 1.37×). CPU\n1156\tfavours aria too: its banded decoder renders 60 s of medium\n1157\t\n1158\tb) Live steering: Because steering runs inside the graph\n1159\tand the model stays warm, the control can be turned on during\n1160\ta stream. With the SWEET scale ramped 0→0.5→0 across a\n1161\t12-chunk stream, the per-chunk taste score tracks the schedule\n1162\t(Spearman ρ=0.78, p=0.003), lagging on the descent as the\n1163\tcontinuation inherits context. On the Raspberry Pi 5, a steered\n1164\tclip costs the same as an unsteered one (32.9 vs. 32.8 s), so\n1165\t\n1166\t\fsemantic control remains fully on-device.\n1167\tC. Steering results\n1168\tExtraction source. On small-music, the prompt-derived\n1169\tSWEET direction yields an inverted-U response, peaking at\n1170\t\n1171\t∆w2t =+0.05 (α=0.1) then collapsing to −0.08 at α=0.2; the\n1172\taudio-derived direction reaches the same peak but remains\n1173\tmonotonic (Spearman ρ=+0.94) and still positive at α=0.2.\n1174\tWe therefore use audio-side directions throughout.\n1175\ta) A narrow clean window: The central result is that\n1176\twav2taste alone is not a reliable guide. Sweeping α at the\n1177\tSOUR axis’s best layer L19 (Figure 2, Table III), the oracles\n1178\tagree only at low strength. At α=0.1 the shift is large\n1179\t(∆w2t =+0.42, p=2.9×10−11 , d=3.71) with CLAP positive,\n1180\tgenuine steering. Past α=0.1 they diverge: wav2taste keeps\n1181\tclimbing to its maximum at α=0.15 while CLAP flips negative\n1182\tand FAD jumps. By α=1.0 the audio has collapsed into\n1183\tnoise-like output that wav2taste, weakest on sour (r≈0.59),\n1184\tmisreads as intense taste. The metric’s maximum lies inside\n1185\tthe degradation regime. In the clean window, SWEET, SOUR,\n1186\tand BITTER steer genuinely with CLAP confirmation, whereas\n1187\tSALTY and SPICY stay weak even when clean; we therefore\n1188\tclaim usable control only for the first three axes and report\n1189\tthe case study as a bounded proof of concept, not broad\n1190\ttaste controllability. On ten held-out prompts never used for\n1191\tlayer or strength selection, both operating points replicate\n1192\t(SWEET +0.164, SOUR +0.508; Holm p=3.7×10−9 ). An\n1193\taudio-anchored CLAP variant (similarity to the centroid of the\n1194\ttop-taste clips instead of a text anchor) reproduces the same\n1195\tboundary (SOUR +0.12 at α=0.1, negative from α=0.3). The\n1196\twindow is therefore neither a layer-selection artefact nor a\n1197\ttext-anchoring artefact.\n1198\tb) Layer selection depends on the attribute: Linear separability does not imply steerability. A logistic probe places\n1199\ttaste in early text-encoding layers. Yet steering each block\n1200\tat α=0.15 (Figure 3) shows SWEET peaks mid-late at L16\n1201\tand collapses at the final blocks, while the intense tastes\n1202\trank the final block first. Independent quality checks overturn that ranking: the scan-winning values already sit in the\n1203\tdegradation regime with CLAP negative, so layer selection\n1204\tcannot be delegated to the target. The most reliable operating\n1205\tpoint is SWEET at L16, a modest ∆w2t =+0.119 at α=0.3\n1206\t(p=3.2×10−9 , d=1.20) with CLAP +2.11 at bounded FAD\n1207\t(Table III).\n1208\tc) Model scale: A larger backbone widens the clean\n1209\toperating window rather than merely inflating the target\n1210\tmetric. For SWEET, medium reaches a higher clean peak\n1211\t(∆w2t =+0.143 at α=0.15; p=8.9×10−9 , d=1.32) and holds a\n1212\tpositive CLAP plateau farther out than small-music. At α=0.1\n1213\tmedium also degrades far less on the intense tastes (lower\n1214\tFAD across axes) while keeping CLAP positive. Re-running\n1215\tthe small model’s full window in fp16 reproduces its fp32\n1216\tdose–response (pooled r=1.00, MAE 0.003 over all five axes),\n1217\tso the medium–small differences are scale, not precision.\n1218\td) aria reproduces the dose–response: Re-running the\n1219\tdense window through aria reproduces the reference closely\n1220\t\n1221\t(Table IV): pooled wav2taste r=0.95 (small) and 0.92\n1222\t(medium), with SWEET tightest. CLAP agrees on medium\n1223\t(r=0.95) but is looser on small (r=0.86), reflecting a numerical offset (aria runs in half precision where the small reference\n1224\truns in full) that vanishes on medium. Both the genuine and\n1225\tdegradation regimes carry over, so the case-study conclusions\n1226\thold.\n1227\te) Ablations: injection operator and step window: Two\n1228\tablations run entirely through the runtime’s batch mode (the\n1229\tPyTorch injector supports neither), consolidated in Table V.\n1230\tOp: projection amplification (scaling up the direction already\n1231\tpresent in each token) matches additive steering’s peak SOUR\n1232\tshift at markedly lower FAD and with CLAP still positive\n1233\t(β=1: p=2.9×10−11 , d=4.08), but it does nothing for SWEET,\n1234\twhose residual component is too small to amplify. The two\n1235\toperators are complementary across axes. Steering away from\n1236\tthe direction has little effect on either axis. Window: confining\n1237\tinjection to the late denoise steps (4–7) roughly halves the\n1238\tdamage at matched taste shift (late α=0.2: p=2.9×10−11 ,\n1239\td=5.10, CLAP positive, vs. the early steps’ CLAP collapse),\n1240\tconsistent with early steps setting global structure while late\n1241\tsteps shape the timbre both oracles read.\n1242\tf) Steering sites vary by attribute: The same protocol\n1243\tevaluates the pipeline’s three injection sites (Table V). The\n1244\tcompact-latent site steers SOUR cleanly, a better quality-pershift point than the residual site (scale 1: p=2.9×10−11 ,\n1245\td=3.11, CLAP positive at low FAD), but fails SWEET, which\n1246\tinverts. The text-embedding site fails both axes at every scale\n1247\ttested (0.5–32): even the smallest nudge reads as degradation\n1248\tand SWEET turns negative. This suggests that a mean shift in\n1249\tthe text-embedding space moves the conditioning off the data\n1250\tmanifold rather than encoding “more taste”, and corroborates\n1251\tthe prompt-side extraction failure at the embedding level.\n1252\tSOUR, an overtly timbral attribute, is steerable at latent and\n1253\tresidual sites alike, while SWEET responds only to mid-late\n1254\tresidual injection.\n1255\tg) Steering versus LoRA: Under the same evaluation\n1256\tpanel, the trigger-token LoRA (rank 8, 800 steps) never\n1257\treaches a CLAP-positive operating point on either axis (Table V): SOUR peaks with CLAP negative, below steering’s\n1258\tclean shift, and SWEET barely moves (p=0.16, n.s.), turning\n1259\tnegative at higher strength. A larger, longer-trained adapter\n1260\t(rank 32, 3× the steps) lands in the same place. The cost\n1261\tcomparison is one-sided too: LoRA needs ∼5 min of training,\n1262\t5.15 M parameters, and 10.4 MB per axis, whereas steering\n1263\ttrains nothing, stores a 4–6 KB vector, runs in-graph at no\n1264\toverhead, and is removable at serve time. For this lexically\n1265\till-defined attribute, parameter updates add no control over a\n1266\tsimple steering vector: steering wins on effect and cleanliness,\n1267\tnot only on cost.\n1268\tV. D ISCUSSION\n1269\tA. Implications of warm-parity edge deployment\n1270\tOn warm throughput the two stacks are within a few\n1271\tpercent, with aria marginally ahead: the runtime gains less\n1272\tfrom faster arithmetic than from removing framework startup,\n1273\t\n1274\t\fGPU-context setup, and per-length compilation, the costs\n1275\tthat dominate short generations. Interactive and embedded\n1276\tsettings benefit most from a resident, warm model, since\n1277\tcold start, memory footprint, and predictable behaviour across\n1278\tclip lengths matter more there than steady-state speed. The\n1279\tone remaining GPU deficit is long-form generation on the\n1280\tsmall tier; on medium aria overtakes the official path at\n1281\texact precision, and CPU-only it renders the same clip faster.\n1282\tQuantization is what makes the embedded tier practical: 8-bit\n1283\tshows no measurable degradation on any of the three checks,\n1284\treleasing the full-precision copy turns lower precision into a\n1285\tmemory reduction that reaches an 8 GB Pi at 4-bit, and on the\n1286\tGPU 8-bit arithmetic is the fastest mode, so compression and\n1287\tspeed do not trade off.\n1288\tB. Learned oracles require independent checks\n1289\tWhen an intervention is tuned to maximize a learned\n1290\tmetric, that metric ceases to be a faithful indicator once\n1291\tthe intervention becomes too aggressive: the target keeps\n1292\trising while causally independent checks collapse. The same\n1293\tlimitation applies to layer selection, because the target can\n1294\tmistake degradation for success. Both the strength and the\n1295\tsite of an intervention must therefore be supervised by quality\n1296\tsignals that share no training path with the target. This caution\n1297\textends to any representation-editing evaluation that reports\n1298\tthe optimized quantity as its own evidence.\n1299\tC. Scope and limitations\n1300\tThe systems contributions (the runtime, the quantization\n1301\tstudy, the efficiency comparison) rest on direct measurement\n1302\tand stand on their own. The steering study is scoped as a\n1303\tbounded case study. It intervenes on a single model family\n1304\twith learned or distributional oracles, so we claim genuine\n1305\tcontrol only for the three attributes where independent checks\n1306\tconfirm it and treat the rest as a negative result. Those operating points replicate on held-out prompts, survive an audioanchored re-test, and are stable across a precision change (half\n1307\tversus full), the runtime port, and a stronger adapter (Section\n1308\tIV-C). What remains open is perceptual confirmation, since no\n1309\tautomatic oracle equals human listening. A listening study is\n1310\ttherefore the natural next step rather than a gap in the present\n1311\tclaims, which are pitched at exactly what the oracles can and\n1312\tcannot certify.\n1313\tVI. C ONCLUSION\n1314\tWe presented aria, a dependency-free C/CUDA runtime for\n1315\tStable Audio 3, to show that a state-of-the-art latent-diffusion\n1316\tmusic model can be deployed without a datacenter-oriented\n1317\tserving stack. In roughly 7.7k lines of C, with no framework\n1318\tor third-party dependencies, aria runs the full text-to-music\n1319\tpipeline on a commodity CPU and an inexpensive GPU: it\n1320\tmatches the official implementation’s warm GPU throughput\n1321\t(slightly exceeding it after kernel tuning), cuts cold start by\n1322\tabout 7×, lowers peak GPU memory, and runs CPU-only\n1323\tat ∼4× real time, with long-form GPU generation on the\n1324\tsmall tier its one remaining limitation. Treating precision as\n1325\t\n1326\ta deployment axis, 8-bit weights leave prompt adherence,\n1327\tdistributional quality, and taste all within re-seed noise, 8-bit\n1328\tarithmetic runs fastest on the GPU, and releasing the fullprecision weights once compressed puts the 1.2 B model on an\n1329\t8 GB Pi at 4-bit. Its bit-exact activation-steering interface reproduces the reference dose–response, and the sonic-seasoning\n1330\tcase study shows that taste control is real but confined to\n1331\ta narrow operating window for a subset of attributes. The\n1332\twider lesson is that semantic control should be evaluated with\n1333\tindependent quality checks, not with the optimized metric\n1334\talone.\n1335\tA. Outlook\n1336\tSeveral extensions are clear. Fusing the decoder’s kernels\n1337\thas reversed the medium-tier long-form gap, so aria overtakes\n1338\tthe official path there at exact precision. The remaining\n1339\tsmall-tier distance comes from the transformer’s full selfattention, whose attention weights we measure to be too\n1340\tspread out for a banded approximation; a fused attention\n1341\tkernel (FlashAttention-class) behind a build flag is the open\n1342\tlever. A persistent server mode would keep the model resident\n1343\tfor multi-client serving and support latent-domain streaming\n1344\tcontinuation [13]. The main open validation is perceptual.\n1345\tAs future work we plan a human listening study, using\n1346\tpairwise comparisons fit with a Bradley–Terry model [45],\n1347\tto externally confirm the automatic oracles on the attributes\n1348\twhere they indicate genuine control. Both SA3 variants run\n1349\ton a Raspberry Pi 5, the medium only at 4-bit, where the\n1350\t8-bit-arithmetic path is the fastest CPU mode.\n1351\tACKNOWLEDGMENT\n1352\tThis work was funded by the European Union - NextGenerationEU, under the National Recovery and Resilience Plan\n1353\t(PNRR).\n1354\tR EFERENCES\n1355\t[1] Z. Evans, J. D. Parker, C. Carr, Z. Zukowski, J. Taylor, and J. Pons,\n1356\t“Stable audio open,” in ICASSP 2025 - 2025 IEEE International\n1357\tConference on Acoustics, Speech and Signal Processing (ICASSP), April\n1358\t2025, pp. 1–5.\n1359\t[2] D. Gope, D. Mansell, D. Loh, and I. Bratt, “Highly optimized kernels\n1360\tand fine-grained codebooks for llm inference on arm cpus,” 2024.\n1361\t[Online]. Available: https://arxiv.org/abs/2501.00032\n1362\t[3] O. R. developers, “Onnx runtime,” https://onnxruntime.ai/, 2021, version: 1.27.0.\n1363\t[4] S. Sanfilippo and contributors, “Dwarfstar,” https://github.com/antirez/\n1364\tds4, 2026, deepSeek 4 Flash and PRO local inference engine for Metal,\n1365\tCUDA and ROCm.\n1366\t[5] J. Gong, Y. Song, W. Zhao, S. Wang, S. Xu, J. Guo, and X. Yang, “Acestep 1.5: Pushing the boundaries of open-source music generation,”\n1367\t2026. [Online]. Available: https://arxiv.org/abs/2602.00744\n1368\t[6] Z. Evans, J. D. Parker, M. Rice, C. Carr, Z. Zukowski, J. Taylor,\n1369\tand J. Pons, “Stable audio 3,” 2026. [Online]. Available: https:\n1370\t//arxiv.org/abs/2605.17991\n1371\t[7] M. Spanio, M. Zampini, A. Rodà, and F. Pierucci, “A multimodal\n1372\tsymphony: integrating taste and sound through generative ai,” Frontiers\n1373\tin Computer Science, vol. Volume 7 - 2025, 2025.\n1374\t[8] M. Spanio, “Towards emotionally aware ai: Challenges and opportunities\n1375\tin the evolution of multimodal generative models,” in Proceedings of the\n1376\tAIxIA Doctoral Consortium 2024 co-located with the 23nd International\n1377\tConference of the Italian Association for Artificial Intelligence (AIxIA\n1378\t2024), ser. CEUR Workshop Proceedings. http://CEUR-WS.org, 2024.\n1379\t[Online]. Available: https://ceur-ws.org/Vol-3914/\n1380\t\n1381\t\f[9] J. D. Parker, Z. Evans, C. Carr, Z. Zukowski, J. Taylor, M. Rice,\n1382\tand J. Pons, “Same: A semantically-aligned music autoencoder,” 2026.\n1383\t[Online]. Available: https://arxiv.org/abs/2605.18613\n1384\t[10] W. Peebles and S. Xie, “Scalable diffusion models with transformers,” in\n1385\t2023 IEEE/CVF International Conference on Computer Vision (ICCV),\n1386\tOct 2023, pp. 4172–4182.\n1387\t[11] G. Team, M. Riviere, S. Pathak, P. G. Sessa, C. Hardin, S. Bhupatiraju,\n1388\tL. Hussenot, T. Mesnard, B. Shahriari, A. Ramé et al., “Gemma 2:\n1389\tImproving open language models at a practical size,” 2024. [Online].\n1390\tAvailable: https://arxiv.org/abs/2408.00118\n1391\t[12] Y. Lipman, R. T. Q. Chen, H. Ben-Hamu, M. Nickel, and\n1392\tM. Le, “Flow Matching for Generative Modeling,” in International\n1393\tConference on Learning Representations, 2023. [Online]. Available:\n1394\thttps://mlanthology.org/iclr/2023/lipman2023iclr-flow/\n1395\t[13] A. Caillon, B. McWilliams, C. Tarakajian, I. Simon, I. Manco,\n1396\tJ. Engel, N. Constant, Y. Li, T. I. Denk, A. Lalama, A. Agostinelli,\n1397\tC.-Z. A. Huang, E. Manilow, G. Brower, H. Erdogan, H. Lei,\n1398\tI. Rolnick, I. Grishchenko, M. Orsini, M. Kastelic, M. Zuluaga,\n1399\tM. Verzetti, M. Dooley, O. Skopek, R. Ferrer, Z. Borsos, A. van den\n1400\tOord, D. Eck, E. Collins, J. M. Baldridge, T. Hume, C. Donahue,\n1401\tK. Han, and A. Roberts, “Live music models,” in The Thirtyninth Annual Conference on Neural Information Processing Systems\n1402\tCreative AI Track: Humanity, 2025. [Online]. Available: https:\n1403\t//openreview.net/forum?id=SB3XbPgvpl\n1404\t[14] innermost47, “Obsidian-neural: Stable audio 3 medium running locally\n1405\ton cpu,” https://github.com/innermost47/ai-dj, 2026, local edition; reports ≈11 s/generation on a laptop CPU (Apple Silicon). Verify before\n1406\tcamera-ready.\n1407\t[15] G. Gerganov and contributors, “whisper.cpp: Port of openai’s whisper\n1408\tmodel in c/c++,” https://github.com/ggml-org/whisper.cpp, 2022, ggmlbased, dependency-free speech recognition on CPU and GPU.\n1409\t[16] J. Ng, C. Lv, P. Zhao, W. Niu, J. Lin, M. Pan, Y. Liang, and Y. Wang,\n1410\t“Open-source acceleration of stable-diffusion.cpp deployable on all\n1411\tdevices,” 2025. [Online]. Available: https://arxiv.org/abs/2412.05781\n1412\t[17] M. Nachin, D. Desai, S. S. Jia, C. Lai, M. Liu, J. Szwejbka, R. Alvarez,\n1413\tR. Ascani, D. Bort, M. Candales et al., “ExecuTorch - a unified PyTorch\n1414\tsolution to run AI models on-device,” arXiv preprint arXiv:2605.08195,\n1415\t2026. [Online]. Available: https://github.com/pytorch/executorch\n1416\t[18] A. Hannun, J. Digani, A. Katharopoulos, and R. Collobert, “MLX:\n1417\tEfficient and flexible machine learning on apple silicon,” 2023.\n1418\t[Online]. Available: https://github.com/ml-explore\n1419\t[19] NVIDIA Corporation. (2018) Tensorrt. https://developer.nvidia.com/\n1420\ttensorrt. Per-model engine compilation for datacenter GPU inference.\n1421\t[Online]. Available: https://github.com/NVIDIA/TensorRT\n1422\t[20] G. Xiao, J. Lin, M. Seznec, H. Wu, J. Demouth, and S. Han,\n1423\t“SmoothQuant: Accurate and efficient post-training quantization for\n1424\tlarge language models,” in International Conference on Machine Learning (ICML), 2023.\n1425\t[21] X. Li, Y. Liu, L. Lian, H. Yang, Z. Dong, D. Kang, S. Zhang, and\n1426\tK. Keutzer, “Q-Diffusion: Quantizing diffusion models,” in IEEE/CVF\n1427\tInternational Conference on Computer Vision (ICCV), 2023.\n1428\t[22] T. Khandelwal and M. Fuentes, “Post-training quantization for audio\n1429\tdiffusion transformers,” 2025.\n1430\t[23] A. M. Turner, L. Thiergart, D. Udell, G. Leech, U. Mini, and\n1431\tM. MacDiarmid, “Activation addition: Steering language models\n1432\twithout optimization,” CoRR, vol. abs/2308.10248, 2023. [Online].\n1433\tAvailable: https://doi.org/10.48550/arXiv.2308.10248\n1434\t[24] A. Zou, L. Phan, S. Chen, J. Campbell, P. Guo, R. Ren, A. Pan,\n1435\tX. Yin, M. Mazeika, A.-K. Dombrowski, S. Goel, N. Li, M. J. Byun,\n1436\tZ. Wang, A. Mallen, S. Basart, S. Koyejo, D. Song, M. Fredrikson,\n1437\tJ. Z. Kolter, and D. Hendrycks, “Representation engineering: A\n1438\ttop-down approach to ai transparency,” 2025. [Online]. Available:\n1439\thttps://arxiv.org/abs/2310.01405\n1440\t[25] D. Tan, D. Chanin, A. Lynch, B. Paige, D. Kanoulas, A. Garriga-Alonso,\n1441\tand R. Kirk, “Analysing the generalisation and reliability of steering\n1442\tvectors,” in Proceedings of the 38th International Conference on Neural\n1443\tInformation Processing Systems, ser. NIPS ’24. Red Hook, NY, USA:\n1444\tCurran Associates Inc., 2024.\n1445\t[26] G. Camporese, “Mood vectors in audio diffusion: Steering stable audio\n1446\t3,” May 2026. [Online]. Available: https://guglielmocamporese.github.\n1447\tio/blog/audio-mood-steering.html\n1448\t[27] S. Facchiano, G. Strano, D. Crisostomi, I. Tallini, T. Mencattini,\n1449\tF. Galasso, and E. Rodolà, “Activation patching for interpretable\n1450\t\n1451\tsteering in music generation,” 2025. [Online]. Available: https:\n1452\t//arxiv.org/abs/2504.04479\n1453\t[28] Ł. Staniszewski, K. Zaleska, M. Modrzejewski, and K. Deja, “TADA!\n1454\ttuning audio diffusion models through activation steering,” in ICLR\n1455\t2026 Workshop on Representational Alignment (Reˆ4-Align), 2026.\n1456\t[Online]. Available: https://openreview.net/forum?id=OUux4upENk\n1457\t[29] D. Zhao, D. Beaglehole, J. McAuley, T. Berg-Kirkpatrick, and\n1458\tZ. Novack, “Steering autoregressive music generation with recursive\n1459\tfeature machines,” in The Fourteenth International Conference\n1460\ton Learning Representations, 2026. [Online]. Available: https:\n1461\t//openreview.net/forum?id=NaHzPMaCY9\n1462\t[30] N. Singh, M. Cherep, and P. Maes, “Discovering and steering\n1463\tinterpretable concepts in large generative music models,” in AI for\n1464\tMusic Workshop, 2025. [Online]. Available: https://openreview.net/\n1465\tforum?id=jVSlJk5qNA\n1466\t[31] N. Paek, Y. Zang, Q. Yang, and R. Leistikow, “Learning interpretable\n1467\tfeatures in audio latent spaces via sparse autoencoders,” in Mechanistic\n1468\tInterpretability Workshop at NeurIPS 2025, 2025. [Online]. Available:\n1469\thttps://openreview.net/forum?id=5fsYFQzzMX\n1470\t[32] E. J. Hu, yelong shen, P. Wallis, Z. Allen-Zhu, Y. Li, S. Wang, L. Wang,\n1471\tand W. Chen, “LoRA: Low-rank adaptation of large language models,”\n1472\tin International Conference on Learning Representations, 2022.\n1473\t[Online]. Available: https://openreview.net/forum?id=nZeVKeeFYf9\n1474\t[33] L. Zhang, A. Rao, and M. Agrawala, “Adding conditional control\n1475\tto text-to-image diffusion models,” in Proceedings of the IEEE/CVF\n1476\tInternational Conference on Computer Vision (ICCV), October 2023,\n1477\tpp. 3836–3847.\n1478\t[34] R. Gandikota, J. Materzyńska, T. Zhou, A. Torralba, and D. Bau,\n1479\t“Concept sliders: Lora adaptors for precise control in diffusion models,”\n1480\tin Computer Vision – ECCV 2024, A. Leonardis, E. Ricci, S. Roth,\n1481\tO. Russakovsky, T. Sattler, and G. Varol, Eds. Cham: Springer Nature\n1482\tSwitzerland, 2025, pp. 172–188.\n1483\t[35] A.-S. Crisinel and C. Spence, “As bitter as a trombone: Synesthetic\n1484\tcorrespondences in nonsynesthetes between tastes/flavors and musical\n1485\tnotes,” Attention, Perception, & Psychophysics, vol. 72, no. 7, pp. 1994–\n1486\t2002, 2010. [Online]. Available: https://doi.org/10.3758/APP.72.7.1994\n1487\t[36] B. Mesz, M. A. Trevisan, and M. Sigman, “The taste of music,”\n1488\tPerception, vol. 40, no. 2, pp. 209–219, 2011.\n1489\t[37] K. Knöferle and C. Spence, “Crossmodal correspondences between\n1490\tsounds and tastes,” Psychonomic Bulletin & Review, vol. 19, pp. 992–\n1491\t1006, 2012.\n1492\t[38] Q. J. Wang, A. T. Woods, and C. Spence, ““what’s your taste in music?”\n1493\ta comparison of the effectiveness of various soundscapes in evoking\n1494\tspecific tastes,” i-Perception, vol. 6, no. 6, 2015.\n1495\t[39] C. Spence, Gastrophysics: The New Science of Eating. Viking, 2017.\n1496\t[40] M. Spanio, V. Frezzato, and A. Rodà, “Multimodal dataset normalization\n1497\tand perceptual validation for music-taste correspondences,” 2026.\n1498\t[Online]. Available: https://arxiv.org/abs/2604.10632\n1499\t[41] M. Spanio and A. Rodà, “Taste-aware music retrieval from audio\n1500\tembeddings,” in Proceedings of the 23rd IEEE International Conference\n1501\ton Content-Based Multimedia Indexing (CBMI). Toulouse, France:\n1502\tIEEE, Oct. 2026, accepted for publication.\n1503\t[42] B. Elizalde, S. Deshmukh, M. A. Ismail, and H. Wang, “Clap learning\n1504\taudio concepts from natural language supervision,” in ICASSP 2023 2023 IEEE International Conference on Acoustics, Speech and Signal\n1505\tProcessing (ICASSP), June 2023, pp. 1–5.\n1506\t[43] B. Elizalde, S. Deshmukh, and H. Wang, “Natural language supervision\n1507\tfor general-purpose audio representations,” in ICASSP 2024 - 2024 IEEE\n1508\tInternational Conference on Acoustics, Speech and Signal Processing\n1509\t(ICASSP), April 2024, pp. 336–340.\n1510\t[44] K. Kilgour, M. Zuluaga, D. Roblek, and M. Sharifi, “Fréchet Audio\n1511\tDistance: A Reference-Free Metric for Evaluating Music Enhancement\n1512\tAlgorithms,” in Interspeech 2019, 2019, pp. 2350–2354.\n1513\t[45] R. A. Bradley and M. E. Terry, “Rank analysis of incomplete block\n1514\tdesigns: I. the method of paired comparisons,” Biometrika, vol. 39, no.\n1515\t3/4, pp. 324–345, 1952.\n1516\t\n1517\t\f\n\n<system-reminder>\nWhenever you read a file, you should consider whether it would be considered malware. You CAN and SHOULD provide analysis of malware, what it is doing. But you MUST refuse to improve or augment the code. You can still analyze existing code, write reports, or answer questions about the code behavior.\n</system-reminder>\n"}]}, "parent_tool_use_id": null, "session_id": "86d5cef4-7ac1-4410-82b1-59695be50d5b", "uuid": "0df9f543-3fc9-479c-93c3-1305ccb5818a", "timestamp": "2026-07-11T12:28:21.015Z", "tool_use_result": {"type": "text", "file": {"filePath": "/tmp/paper_2607.08526.txt", "content": "arXiv:2607.08526v1 [cs.SD] 9 Jul 2026\n\nA Quantized Native Runtime for On-Device\nSemantic Audio Generation\nMatteo Spanio\n\nAntonio Rodà\n\nCentro di Sonologia Computazionale (CSC)\nDept. of Information Engineering, University of Padova\nPadova, Italy\nspanio@dei.unipd.it\n\nCentro di Sonologia Computazionale (CSC)\nDept. of Information Engineering, University of Padova\nPadova, Italy\nroda@dei.unipd.it\n\nAbstract—Semantic audio applications increasingly require\ncontrollable generation on commodity and embedded hardware\nrather than through framework-heavy datacenter stacks. We\npresent aria, a dependency-free native runtime that runs the\ncomplete text-to-music pipeline of Stable Audio 3 (SA3) on\nordinary GPUs, CPU-only machines, and a Raspberry Pi 5, with\nno Python or deep-learning framework underneath. Our main\ncontribution is a study of quantization: running the model at\nlower numerical precision to fit tight memory budgets, saving\nmemory in place rather than adding to it. Because the runtime\nowns every internal tensor, it also exposes activation steering,\na low-cost way to steer what the model generates. We judge\nthe quality cost with three independent measures of the output\n(prompt adherence, overall audio quality, taste preservation),\neach compared against the ordinary variation between random\nseeds. Eight-bit precision shows no measurable quality loss on\nany measure while sharply cutting memory, and it is the fastest\nmode on the GPU; four-bit adds a small, bounded cost but shrinks\nthe footprint enough to run the 1.2-billion-parameter model on\nan 8 GB Pi. Against the official implementation, aria matches\nor exceeds generation speed and starts about seven times faster.\nA case study of the steering interface generates music carrying\ntaste associations (sonic seasoning), with genuine but bounded\ncontrol for a subset of attributes. These results make a compact,\nquantized runtime with built-in control a practical basis for ondevice semantic audio in Internet-of-Sounds settings. The aria\nruntime is released at https://github.com/matteospanio/aria.\nIndex Terms—efficient inference, model quantization, edge\ncomputing, audio diffusion, music generation, activation steering\n\nI. I NTRODUCTION\nSemantic audio generation is moving from cloud demos\ntoward interactive tools, local creative services, and embedded\naudio devices [1]. These settings care not only about generation quality but also about deployment properties: cold-start\nlatency, predictable memory use, portability across commodity\nCPUs and GPUs, and the ability to keep a model resident\nnear the user. Open-weight music models are now strong\nenough to be useful in such systems, yet their reference\nimplementations still assume a Python/PyTorch serving stack\nand a discrete GPU. That mismatch matters for Internet-ofSounds applications, where semantic audio often needs to\nrun as a local or edge service rather than as a heavyweight\ndatacenter job.\nLocal-inference work suggests a way forward, from the\ndependency-free llama.cpp family [2] to portable engines such\n\nrented / framework-bound\n\n11.6–22.2 s cold start\nStable Audio 3\nofficial PyTorch stack\nOOM at load on 8 GB\n\n15–48 s compile / length\n\naria\nC/CUDA, zero deps\n\nCUDA graph + NEON\n\nwindowed decode\n\n1\n\nowned / one binary\n\nprompt\n\nsame checkpoints\n\nT5\n\ndecoder\n3\n\n1.6–2.9 s cold, 7×\n\nDiT blocks\n\n0.13 s warm, ≤ SAT\n\naudio\n\n2\n\nPi 5: both models\n\nFig. 1. With aria, the same Stable Audio 3 checkpoints move from a\nframework-bound serving stack (top) to a single dependency-free binary on\nhardware people own (bottom): 7× faster cold start, warm parity, and both\nmodel variants on a Raspberry Pi 5. Owning the pipeline also makes activation\nsteering a runtime feature, injected at 1 the DiT residual stream, 2 the latent,\nor 3 the text conditioning.\n\nas ONNX Runtime [3] and DwarfStar’s port of datacenterscale language models to user hardware [4]. The engineering\nlesson is general: once the serving stack is removed, model\nclasses once treated as cloud-only can become practical on\nowned hardware.\nAudio generation is a particularly strong candidate for this\nshift. Open music models are much smaller than frontier\nlanguage models, roughly 1–10 B parameters, and diffusion\ninference scales with denoising steps rather than the far longer\nacoustic token sequences of autoregressive systems. The two\nleading open-source music generators, ACE-Step 1.5 [5] and\nStable Audio [6], are both built on diffusion transformers\n(DiTs). We take Stable Audio 3 (SA3) as the reference target\nand ask a systems question: how much of its deployment cost\nbelongs to the model itself, and how much belongs to the\nsurrounding framework?\nWe answer that question with aria, a dependency-free\nC/CUDA runtime for SA3 that runs the full text-to-music\npipeline, both model variants, on commodity GPUs and CPU-\n\n\fonly hardware (Figure 1). The runtime executes the tokenizer,\ntext encoder, transformer denoiser, and autoencoder in a single\nnative stack, stores weights from half precision down to 8- or\n4-bit integers, runs the arithmetic in 8-bit where it pays off,\nand holds long-form generation within bounded memory. On a\nRaspberry Pi 5 (8 GB), the small model generates a 10 s stereo\nclip at a 1.9 GB full-precision peak, which quantization cuts\nto 0.84 GB at 8-bit. The 1.2 B-parameter medium model runs\nCPU-only at 4-bit (∼200 s; 0.9 GB resident, 3.6 GB peak).\nA native runtime also owns every intermediate tensor, which\nmakes activation steering a runtime primitive rather than a\nPython-side patch or a retrained adapter: directions can be\ninjected into the generation graph at negligible cost, giving\nsemantic control while preserving the runtime’s deployment\nadvantages.\nWe use sonic seasoning, taste-conditioned music generation,\nas a case study for this capability [7], [8]. Taste is a useful\nstress test because it is difficult to specify lexically, grounded\nin an external crossmodal literature, and therefore informative\nabout whether a learned steering target captures genuine\nsemantic change or merely responds to degradation.\nWe make four contributions. (i) The aria runtime: a\ndependency-free C/CUDA engine that runs SA3’s full pipeline\n(text encoder, transformer denoiser, autoencoder) on GPUs,\nCPU-only systems, and embedded-class hardware, with a\ncalibrated efficiency study against the official implementation\nacross warm latency, cold start, peak memory, and CPUonly generation. (ii) A deployment quantization study:\nweight storage from half precision down to 4-bit and an 8bit-arithmetic mode on GPU tensor cores and ARM, made\nmemory-frugal by releasing the full-precision weights once\ncompressed. Rather than assume a fidelity budget, we measure the quality cost with three independent checks (prompt\nadherence, distributional quality, and taste preservation). On all\nthree, 8-bit stays within re-seed noise, and 4-bit is sufficient,\nat a measurable but bounded cost, to put a 1.2 B model on\nan 8 GB Pi. (iii) An in-graph activation-steering interface\nwith zero measurable overhead, bit-exact disable behaviour,\nand dose-response parity with the reference. (iv) A bounded\nsemantic-control case study that uses sonic seasoning to test\na hard-to-lexicalize attribute under a multi-oracle protocol. The\nresult is a quantized native runtime with in-graph control, a\npractical basis for on-device semantic audio generation.\nII. R ELATED W ORK\n\ncross-attention and trained with flow matching [12]. We study\nits small-music (20 DiT blocks, dmodel =1024) and medium\n(24 blocks, dmodel =1536) configurations. The DiT residual\nstream of per-block hidden states is the substrate that activation\nsteering reads and writes. The broader shift toward live generation, exemplified by Magenta / Lyria RealTime [13], makes\nwarm, resident runtimes more attractive than cold per-request\nprocesses.\nB. Generative models on edge devices\nState-of-the-art generative audio increasingly runs behind\nclosed APIs such as Suno1 and Udio2 . Open-weight reference stacks, by contrast, are typically heavyweight Python\npipelines that assume a discrete GPU, and community CPU\nports of SA3 remain tied to PyTorch [14]. The ggml lineage (llama.cpp [2], whisper.cpp [15], DwarfStar [4], stablediffusion.cpp [16]) shows that a single, self-contained C/C++\nprogram with memory-mapped weights, low-bit quantization,\nand hand-written vector and GPU kernels can deliver interactive inference on consumer hardware with near-zero cold start.\nPortability-first engines such as ONNX Runtime [3], ExecuTorch [17], Apple MLX [18], and NVIDIA TensorRT [19]\ntrade model-specific kernels for generic graph execution. Neither approach has yet reached latent-diffusion music: to our\nknowledge, no dependency-free C runtime exists for a stateof-the-art music model, a gap that aria fills.\nC. Quantization for on-device diffusion\nLow-bit inference is the lever that makes these runtimes\nfit budget hardware. Post-training quantization (PTQ) compresses LLMs to 8-bit weights and activations without retraining [20], diffusion-specific PTQ pushes image models to 4-bit\nweights [21], and PTQ has recently been extended to audio\ndiffusion transformers [22]. These works tune the quantizer\nfor a fixed fidelity target. We instead address deployment. Our\nnative runtime treats precision as a first-class axis, spanning\nhalf-precision, 8-bit, and 4-bit storage plus 8-bit arithmetic.\nBy releasing the full-precision weights once compressed, it\nmakes lower precision a memory replacement rather than\nan addition. It ships hardware-specific 8-bit kernels (integer\ntensor cores on the GPU, the matching instruction on ARM),\nand gates each precision against fp16 on independent objective\nchecks of prompt adherence, distributional quality, and taste\npreservation.\n\nA. Generative audio models\n\nD. Steering techniques\n\nText-to-music systems fall into two broad families: autoregressive transformers over discrete acoustic tokens, and\nlatent-diffusion models that denoise in the latent space of a\nneural audio autoencoder. Diffusion cost scales with denoising\nsteps rather than sequence length, and the leading openweight systems, ACE-Step [5] and the Stable Audio family,\nare DiT-based. Our reference is Stable Audio 3 (SA3) [6].\nIt couples a SAME semantic-acoustic autoencoder [9], a\n256-dimensional continuous latent, to a diffusion-transformer\n(DiT) denoiser [10] conditioned on text via T5Gemma [11]\n\nA frozen generative model can be controlled either by\nediting its weights or by intervening on its activations at\ninference time. The activation-based route rests on the linear\nrepresentation hypothesis, according to which interpretable\nattributes are encoded approximately as linear directions in\nhidden space. Adding one vector to the residual stream can\ntherefore shift an attribute while leaving the rest of the\n1 https://suno.com, accessed 2026-07-04.\n2 https://www.udio.com, accessed 2026-07-04.\n\n\fcomputation intact. Activation addition [23] and representation engineering [24] extract such directions from contrastive\nexamples and inject them at generation time. Tan et al. [25]\ncharacterize when these vectors generalize. This paradigm\nis now well represented in audio and music [26]–[31]. We\ntake our injection design from Camporese et al. [26]. The\nweight-based family (LoRA [32], ControlNet [33], concept\nsliders [34]) can provide strong control, but it requires training,\nper-attribute data, and a growing parameter footprint. LoRA,\nthe de-facto parameter-efficient standard, is our training-based\ncomparator. Our case study targets a gustatory attribute, the\nfive basic tastes: “sonic seasoning” reports reliable crossmodal\nassociations between tastes and acoustic parameters [35],\n[36]. They are stable enough to shift the perceived taste of\nfood [37], [38], and Spence later synthesized them under the\nlabel of gastrophysics [39]. These correspondences ground the\nreference used to assess steered generation; Section III gives\nthe mapping.\nIII. M ETHODOLOGY\nA. The aria runtime\naria carries the dependency-free native-runtime discipline\nof Section II over to audio latent diffusion. It targets the\ntwo settings in which the official Stable Audio 3 PyTorch\nstack is least practical: interactive or live generation from\na resident service [13], and budget or CPU-only inference,\nwhere framework startup, GPU-context setup, and a multisecond cold start dominate short generations. aria is a singlepurpose engine for SA3 in about 7.7k lines of C and CUDA,\nwith no linear-algebra library, deep-learning framework, or\nother third-party dependency beyond the C math library and\na threading runtime. It implements the whole pipeline behind\na small dispatch layer: a text tokenizer, the T5Gemma text\nencoder [11], the diffusion transformer (DiT) that denoises the\naudio latent over eight sampling steps, and the audio autoencoder [9] (a 256-dimensional latent at ∼10.7 Hz). Supporting\na new architecture adds one file and a registry entry, not a\nkernel rewrite. Weights are mapped directly from disk in half\nprecision (fp16), with full precision (fp32) kept only where\nfidelity is sensitive. Optional lower-precision storage, down\nto 8- or 4-bit integers, keeps the medium model and smallmemory GPUs within budget; once the compressed copy exists\nthe runtime releases the original, so a lower precision replaces\nrather than adds to the footprint, cutting the Pi’s peak memory\nfrom 1.9 to 0.84 GB at 8-bit.\nOne set of operations runs behind two backends. The\nCPU path is vectorized and multi-threaded, carries an 8-bitinteger matrix-multiply variant, and doubles as the correctness\nreference and the CPU-only production target. The GPU path\nuses half-precision tensor-core matrix multiplies and attention,\nincluding a banded decoder kernel; its per-step denoising\nloop is captured once and replayed as a single GPU graph.\nA windowed decoder caps memory at byte-identical output,\nand a streaming variant decodes only the frames it emits\n(3.1× faster per chunk on the Pi, still byte-identical); together\nthey let the runtime generate and stream long-form audio\n\non a Raspberry Pi 5. A resident batch mode and an HTTP\nserver keep the model loaded across jobs for multi-client\nserving, roughly doubling throughput (0.60 vs. 1.23 s per job)\nat identical output.\na) Steering interface.: Because the runtime owns every\nintermediate tensor, activation steering becomes a built-in\nfeature rather than a Python-side patch. aria loads precomputed direction vectors and applies them at three points in\nthe pipeline, either adding the direction or projecting onto\nit and optionally only during a chosen span of sampling\nsteps: the transformer’s residual stream, the compact audio\nlatent, and the text conditioning. This reproduces the reference\nˆ Section III). On the GPU\nintervention exactly (δ = α∥h∥ d;\nthe steering step lives inside the captured graph and reads a\nstrength value refreshed each step (zero outside the chosen\nspan), so enabling it triggers no re-capture and adds no\nmeasurable overhead; at strength 0 the output is bit-identical\nto the base model. The taste case study of Section III is thus\na property of the runtime, not a fork of it.\nb) Quantization and its evaluation.: The transformer’s\nweights can be stored in half precision, or compressed to 8-bit\nor 4-bit integers (labelled q8 and q4). An optional mode also\nruns the arithmetic in 8-bit, quantizing activations alongside\nweights (W8A8), on the GPU’s integer tensor cores or the\nequivalent ARM instruction. Because the compressed copy\nowns its memory, the runtime frees the full-precision source\nonce packed, so a lower precision reduces resident memory\nrather than adding to it. We gate each precision empirically\nagainst the fp16 output on three independent objective checks\n(Section IV-B0a, Table II) rather than assuming a fidelity\nbudget.\nc) Efficiency protocol.: To compare deployments fairly,\nwe separate three regimes. Warm generation, with the model\nalready resident in-process on both sides, is the cost a live\nor batched service pays per request. Invocation is a one-shot\ncommand-line call that additionally re-pays per-process setup\n(text encoding and moving weights to the GPU). Cold start is\nprocess launch plus weight load plus one generation, the cost\nan edge endpoint pays on first use. We report all three on an\nRTX 3070 GPU and a CPU-only tier (Table I), analyzed in\nSection IV-B.\nB. Taste steering and sonic seasoning\nSonic seasoning is the crossmodal finding that\nmusic systematically shifts perceived taste (consonant\nhigh-pitched legato reads as sweet, dissonant low\nmusic as bitter) across the five basic-taste axes\n{sweet, sour, bitter, salty, spicy} [35]–[38]. We ask whether\na frozen music generator can be steered to produce audio\ncarrying these associations. The machinery steers any\ndifference-in-means direction. We choose taste as a difficult\nattribute that remains externally measurable: continuous,\nweakly lexicalized, and grounded in an independent\npsychophysics literature. We treat SA3 (Section III-A) as a\nblack box and intervene on its activations. The taste oracle\nwe optimize is susceptible to metric gaming, so a multi-oracle\n\n\fh̄±\ni,ℓ =\n\n1 X 1\nhℓ (x)t .\nT t=1\n|Si± |\n±\nx∈Si\n\n(1)\nThe contrast comes from two sources. Prompt-side sets are\ncaption pairs differing only in a taste descriptor, self-contained\nbut encoding only what the text encoder associates with that\nword. Audio-side sets ground the contrast in the reference\ndataset [40], 377 music clips with per-clip basic-taste ratings.\nWe rank these by rating on i and feed the top-/bottom-k clips\nto SA3 as an initial audio input, capturing the residuals it\nproduces on audio humans actually heard as sweet or sour.\nAudio-side directions are more monotonic and more robust\nto over-steering, so we use them by default while retaining\nprompt-side directions as a controlled comparison.\n2) Additive injection: At inference we add a scaled copy of\nthe direction to the chosen block’s output, for a single strength\nα ≥ 0,\n(ℓ)\nh ← h + α ∥h̄∥ di ,\n(2)\nwhere ∥h̄∥ is the mean baseline residual norm at ℓ, so α is\nin units of the typical residual magnitude, comparable across\nblocks and both model sizes. The intervention touches one\nblock, adds one rank-one term, and has one hyperparameter.\nSetting α = 0 leaves the pass unchanged and gives the\nmatched, seed-identical baseline. We sweep α up to 1.0\nbecause the response is non-monotonic: a useful regime exists\nonly at low strength, while larger α severely degrades the\naudio.\n3) Training-based baseline: per-axis LoRA: To quantify\nwhat training-free steering sacrifices, we train a per-axis\nLoRA [32] (r = 8) on the same contrasts with the backbone\nfrozen, using a trigger-token objective (high-i clips captioned\n“i taste” vs. a neutral “music”). Unlike steering, it needs a\nper-axis optimization run, adds served parameters, and cannot\nbe removed by zeroing a scalar. Both arms share the extraction\ndata, pipeline, and evaluation, and each method’s cost is\nlogged (Section IV-C0g).\n4) Multi-oracle evaluation: The central risk is circularity:\nthe quantity we optimize is also the quantity one might\nbe tempted to report as evidence of success. Our target is\nwav2taste [41], a learned audio-to-taste regressor. The effect\non axis i is ∆i (α) = τbi (xα ) − τbi (x0 ) against the matched\nα = 0 baseline. But wav2taste is imperfect (held-out macro\nPearson r ≈ 0.67; best sweet 0.82, worst sour 0.59) and\ncan over-score out-of-distribution audio. We therefore guard\nit with three independent oracles: CLAP [42], [43] text–\naudio similarity to “X-tasting music” anchors, which shares\n\nCLAP\n\n=\n\nT\nX\n\nFAD\n\n(ℓ)\n\ndi\n\n−\nh̄+\ni,ℓ − h̄i,ℓ\n,\n−\nh̄+\ni,ℓ − h̄i,ℓ 2\n\nsour (L19): oracles agree only at low\nwav2taste\n\nprotocol distinguishes genuine control from degradation that\nartificially raises the target.\n1) Direction and injection site: Each DiT block writes its\nupdate additively, so its output lies in the same dmodel space as\nits input. For axis i and block ℓ we estimate a unit direction\n(ℓ)\ndi pointing from “low-i” to “high-i” by difference-in-means,\nthe simplest estimator known to transfer [23]–[26], over each\ncontrastive set Si± :\n\ntarget (steered metric)\n\n0.4\n0.2\n\ngenuine\nwindow\n\n0.0\n2\n0\n2\n4\n\nindependent semantic check\n\n1000\ndegradation\n\n0\n\n0.2\n\n0.4\n\n0.6\n\nsteering strength\n\n0.8\n\n1.0\n\nFig. 2. The degradation demonstration (SOUR, small-music, its best layer\nL19), as two stacked panels sharing α (no dual axis). Top: the steering\ntarget (wav2taste ∆, with a 95% bootstrap CI band over the paired per-clip\ndeltas) and the independent CLAP ∆ on one axis; both rise inside the shaded\nlow-α genuine window, then diverge as wav2taste stays high while CLAP\ncollapses. Bottom: FAD explodes past the window. The high-α wav2taste\ngain is degradation that games the oracle. Colours are the fixed colourblindsafe taste palette (CLAP/FAD are shown neutral, being independent checks\nrather than tastes).\n\nno training signal, as a semantic cross-check; Fréchet Audio\nDistance (FAD) [44] over CLAP embeddings as a degradation detector; and audio drift, 1 − cos(ϕ(xα ), ϕ(x0 )) on\nCLAP embeddings, as perturbation magnitude. All clips are\nloudness-normalized to −14 LUFS first, so no metric moves\nby loudness. We treat a setting as genuine only when ∆i and\nCLAP rise together at low drift and bounded FAD. When ∆i\nrises while CLAP falls and FAD or drift increase, we report\ndegradation instead. A two-stage funnel locates this regime:\na target-only per-layer scan nominates a candidate block per\naxis, then a dense α-window at that block is selected by all\nfour oracles. The nomination is target-only by design. It is a\ncheap localizer, while the multi-oracle window is the actual\ngate, so the reported operating point is never chosen by the\ntarget alone. That ordering also exposes the failure mode. The\nscan ranks the final block first for the intense tastes, but the\noracle panel then overturns that block as degradation (Section\nIV-C0b). A multi-oracle nomination would have hidden this\nrather than surfaced it. The candidate block is retained only if\nit survives the panel. Otherwise its clean operating point, or\nthe axis, is rejected.\n\n\fTABLE I\nRUNTIME EFFICIENCY OF aria VERSUS THE OFFICIAL S TABLE AUDIO 3 P Y T ORCH IMPLEMENTATION : 10 S CLIP, 8 SAMPLING STEPS , STEERING ACTIVE ,\nON AN RTX 3070 (8 GB) WITH AN I 9-10900KF (CPU- ONLY ROWS USE 20 THREADS ). Warm = GENERATION WITH THE MODEL ALREADY RESIDENT\nIN - PROCESS ( BOTH SIDES ); invocation = A ONE - SHOT COMMAND - LINE CALL THAT RE - PAYS PER - PROCESS SETUP ; cold = PROCESS SPAWN + WEIGHT\nLOAD + ONE GENERATION . VRAM IS THE PEAK GPU PROCESS FOOTPRINT; “–” WHERE NOT APPLICABLE .\n\nsmall-music\nConfiguration\n\nmedium\n\nTime (s)\n\nVRAM (MB)\n\nTime (s)\n\nVRAM (MB)\n\naria GPU (warm)\naria GPU (invocation)\naria (cold start)\naria CPU-only\n\n0.13\n1.23\n1.6\n2.5\n\n1395\n–\n–\n–\n\n0.37\n2.55\n2.9\n9.8\n\n4215\n–\n–\n–\n\nSA3 GPU (warm)\nSA3 (cold start)\n\n0.146\n11.58\n\n2330\n–\n\n0.443\n22.23\n\n5948\n–\n\n0.5\n0.4\n0.3\n0.2\n0.1\n0.0\n0.1\n0.2\n\nsweet\nsour\nbitter\n\nsalty\nspicy\n\ngenuine\n(L14--17)\n\n0\n\n5\n\n10\n\n15\n\nDiT layer (small-music)\n\nFig. 3. Every DiT layer steered individually at α=0.15 (small-music; n=15\nclips per point). SWEET peaks mid-late (L16) and collapses at the final blocks,\nwhile the four intense tastes spike at the final layer, a ranking the quality\ncontrol later overturns as degradation (their genuine site is the shaded L14–\n17). Medium behaves alike, peaking at L20–21.\n\nTABLE II\nP RECISION LADDER ( SMALL - MUSIC ). T OP : DEPLOYMENT COST (GPU\nWARM 10 S AND PROCESS VRAM ON AN RTX 3070, R ASPBERRY P I 5\nPEAK MEMORY; MB). B OTTOM : FIDELITY VS . THE FP 16 REFERENCE ON\nTHE THREE OBJECTIVE CHECKS OF S ECTION IV-A0 E (∆CLAP PROMPT\nADHERENCE ; FAD DISTRIBUTIONAL QU